messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- No

HTTP methods (based on code):
- HEAD: No
- POST: Yes
- OPTIONS: No
- TRACE: No
- GET: Yes
- PUT: Yes
- DELETE: No
- PATCH: No

Explanation:
- The ManagerController has an explicit method annotation:
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.GET) â€” this makes GET acceptable for the exact path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees (this is getEmployees).
- The same exact path is also mapped for:
  - POST via addEmployee: @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.POST)
  - PUT via editEmployee: @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
  Therefore POST and PUT are acceptable for that path.
- DELETE is only defined for the different path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID} (method deleteEmployee). Because that mapping includes an extra path parameter {employeeID}, DELETE is not mapped to /printshops/{printShopID}/employees and thus is not acceptable for this exact path.
- HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE and PATCH: there are no explicit @RequestMapping methods for these HTTP methods in the controller for this path. Per your instruction to base acceptability on the code (not framework implicit behavior), they are marked as not acceptable.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is No because the controller explicitly declares only specific methods (GET, POST, PUT) for this path rather than a wildcard/all-methods mapping.
